  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash is an IR verification
failure after loop vectorization. The verifier reports: \"PHINode should have one
entry for each predecessor of its parent basic block! %use = phi i64 [ %start2,
%for.body ]\". This indicates the loop-vectorizer mutated the CFG such that the
exit block now has a different predecessor set than before, but an existing PHI
(%use) was not updated to reflect the new predecessors. The reproducer has a
single-exit loop with a trivial loop-invariant PHI in the exit block. After
vectorization, a new predecessor (the 'middle block') is added (when no scalar
epilogue is required), but the PHI still lists the original predecessor (which
may no longer be a predecessor or is insufficient), triggering the
assertion.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe log shows the failure occurs at the
final verification in LoopVectorizePass::processLoop right after executing the
vectorization plan. No other diagnostics are emitted. ScalarEvolution output is
normal. The first transformation point (executePlan + subsequent fix-up)
completes and then verification fails at line 10247. Thus the IR was left in an
inconsistent state by earlier transformation code, particularly inside
executePlan / fixVectorizedLoop.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nIn executePlan, the
skeleton is created via InnerLoopVectorizer::createVectorizedLoopSkeleton, which
(if a scalar epilogue is NOT required) later results in an edge from the newly
created 'middle block' directly to the loop's unique exit block (see the diagram
in comments). When this optional edge is inserted, existing PHIs in the exit
block must gain incoming values for the new predecessor. fixVectorizedLoop only
adjusts:\n- Induction variable users (fixupIVUsers)\n- Live-outs tracked in VPlan
(Plan.getLiveOuts())\nIt does NOT generically update pre-existing PHIs in the
exit block that are loop-invariant pass-throughs (like %use). Therefore, when the
predecessor set changes, those PHIs are stale. In the specific reproducer the
loop-invariant value 'start2' is passed through a PHI with a single incoming from
the original loop latch. After vectorization without scalar epilogue, the exit
block's sole predecessor may become the middle block (or gains an additional
predecessor), and the PHI lacks the required incoming for that predecessor,
violating IR invariants.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Points(s):\nFile:
llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp\nLocation: Inside
InnerLoopVectorizer::fixVectorizedLoop, right after finishing induction variable
fix-ups (after the closing brace of the 'else' block that handles the case where
the middle block edge exists) and before handling live-outs.\nEdit lines
2968-2968 (replace the single '}' line with augmented logic):\nReasoning: This is
the minimal, localized place where we already know whether the middle block->exit
edge exists (i.e. requiresScalarEpilogue(VF.isVector()) is false). We add a
repair loop that ensures every PHI in the exit block has an incoming value for
the new predecessor. Special handling is added for the case where the PHI
previously had only one incoming (simple passthrough) and the predecessor
changed; we update the block rather than adding a second incoming. Otherwise we
add an incoming value (re-using a loop-invariant existing incoming if
possible).\nPatch concept:\nReplace line 2968:\n    }\nwith:\n    }\n    // Fix
missing incoming edges for existing exit-block PHIs after adding\n    // the edge
from LoopMiddleBlock to LoopExitBlock when no scalar epilogue\n    // is
required. Some pre-existing PHIs (e.g. trivial loop-invariant passthrough\n    //
PHIs) are not modeled in VPlan live-outs and were never updated.\n    if
(!Cost->requiresScalarEpilogue(VF.isVector()) && LoopExitBlock) {\n      for
(PHINode &PN : LoopExitBlock->phis()) {\n        // Case 1: PHI had a single
incoming edge from the old predecessor,\n        // but now the only predecessor
is LoopMiddleBlock. Update block.\n        if (PN.getNumIncomingValues() == 1
&&\n            PN.getBasicBlockIndex(LoopMiddleBlock) == -1) {\n          // If
the old incoming block is no longer a predecessor, just redirect.\n
BasicBlock *OnlyPred = *pred_begin(LoopExitBlock);\n          if (OnlyPred ==
LoopMiddleBlock) {\n            PN.setIncomingBlock(0, LoopMiddleBlock);\n
continue;\n          }\n        }\n        // Case 2: Middle block is a new
predecessor but PHI lacks an incoming.\n        if
(PN.getBasicBlockIndex(LoopMiddleBlock) == -1) {\n          Value *V = nullptr;\n
// Prefer a loop-invariant existing incoming value.\n          for (unsigned I =
0; I < PN.getNumIncomingValues(); ++I) {\n            Value *IncV =
PN.getIncomingValue(I);\n            if (OrigLoop->isLoopInvariant(IncV)) { V =
IncV; break; }\n          }\n            if (!V && PN.getNumIncomingValues() >
0)\n              V = PN.getIncomingValue(0);\n          if (V)\n
PN.addIncoming(V, LoopMiddleBlock);\n        }\n      }\n    }\n\n5.
Conclusion:\nThe failure stems from not updating pre-existing exit-block PHIs
after inserting a new predecessor when no scalar epilogue is required. Adding a
targeted fix in fixVectorizedLoop ensures all PHIs include an incoming for
LoopMiddleBlock (or remap the single incoming) thus restoring IR consistency and
preventing the assertion. This localized change maintains existing behavior for
modeled live-outs and reductions and only repairs previously ignored trivial
PHIs.\n",
